erty)."]}]},{"name":"Sulney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Sunley Hill in Kirkdale (North Yorkshire). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Sunnólfr</i> + Old Norse <i>haugr</i> ‘hill, mound’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alison","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a very common medieval name, a Norman French diminutive of   Alice .  Despite its early popularity, it became quite rare in England in the 16th century. However, it survived in Scotland, with the result that until its revival in England in the 20th century it had a strongly Scottish flavour."],"variants":[{"name":"Alyson","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alison ."]},{"name":"Allyson","meanings":["Respelling of   Alison ."]},{"name":"Allison","meanings":["Respelling of   Alison .  This is the more common form of the name in the United States."]},{"name":"Alysoun","meanings":["Medieval spelling of   Alison  , which has enjoyed some currency since the 20th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alison de Sulney was born in 1377, in Over Haddon, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Margaret De Trussell. She married William de Durvassal in 1397, in Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died after 1391, in Spernall, Warwickshire, England."},"et":{"1377–Aft 1391":"1377–pärast 1391","1377